Note:
512-bit Unsigned Integer Arithmetic (Int512)

This module provides 512-bit unsigned integer arithmetic, primarily as a
companion to Int256 for holding intermediate products of 256x256 -> 512
multiplications without precision loss. It is also directly usable for
wider deterministic arithmetic.

Determinism guarantee:
- All operations produce bit-exact identical output for identical input on
  every platform (no floating point, no platform-dependent integer widths,
  no undefined-behavior arithmetic).
- This is the bedrock requirement for consensus-critical state machines
  (smart contracts, distributed ledgers, replicated state machines).

Representation:
- Int512 = pointer to a 64-byte heap-allocated buffer
- 8 little-endian limbs of 64 bits each:
    offset  0: limb[0] = bits 0..63   (least significant)
    offset  8: limb[1] = bits 64..127
    offset 16: limb[2] = bits 128..191
    offset 24: limb[3] = bits 192..255
    offset 32: limb[4] = bits 256..319
    offset 40: limb[5] = bits 320..383
    offset 48: limb[6] = bits 384..447
    offset 56: limb[7] = bits 448..511 (most significant)

@Reasoning
A flat byte buffer with explicit limb offsets was chosen over a struct
representation because:
1. The 64-bit Integer is the only general-purpose integer type the bootstrap
   compiler exposes; limb arithmetic must read/write Integer-sized cells.
2. Carry propagation requires uniform access patterns across all 8 limbs;
   a struct with 8 named fields would force open-coding every loop.
3. The 64-byte aligned allocation matches CPU cache lines on every target
   architecture, giving optimal load/store performance.
4. Serialization to/from byte arrays maps to direct memory_get_byte /
   memory_set_byte calls with no copy.
@End Reasoning
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant INT512_SIZE_BYTES as Integer is 64
Constant INT512_LIMB_COUNT as Integer is 8
Constant INT512_BIT_WIDTH as Integer is 512
Constant INT512_LIMB_BITS as Integer is 64
Constant INT512_HIGH_BIT_MASK as Integer is 0x8000000000000000
Constant INT512_LIMB_MASK_LOW32 as Integer is 0x00000000FFFFFFFF
Constant INT512_OK as Integer is 0
Constant INT512_ERR_NULL as Integer is -1
Constant INT512_ERR_DIVIDE_BY_ZERO as Integer is -2
Constant INT512_ERR_INVALID_SHIFT as Integer is -3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Internal Helpers: Carry/Borrow Computation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_carry_from_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, sum as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute the unsigned overflow (carry) bit from a 64-bit add a+b=sum.
        Returns 1 if (a + b) wrapped past 2^64, otherwise 0. Uses the standard
        bit trick: carry = ((a AND b) OR ((a OR b) AND NOT s)) >> 63, which is
        bit-equivalent to the unsigned comparison (sum < a) without requiring
        an unsigned compare primitive.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        The formula derives from the per-bit truth table of full-adder carry:
        each bit position's carry-out is generated when both inputs are 1, or
        propagated when either input is 1 and the sum bit is 0. Folding over
        all 64 bit positions, the most significant bit of the combined mask is
        the carry-out of the top limb position.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Constant time: 5 bitwise ops + 1 shift. No branches. Branch-predictor
        friendly. Maps to roughly 5 instructions on every supported ISA.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time by construction; safe to use on secret-dependent inputs
        (no data-dependent branches, no data-dependent memory access).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let term1 be a bitwise and b
    Let or_ab be a bitwise or b
    Let not_s be bitwise not sum
    Let term2 be or_ab bitwise and not_s
    Let combined be term1 bitwise or term2
    Let carry_bit be combined shifted right by 63
    Let result be carry_bit bitwise and 1
    Return result
End Process

Process called "int512_borrow_from_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, diff as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute the unsigned borrow bit from a 64-bit subtract a-b=diff.
        Returns 1 if a was unsigned-less-than b, otherwise 0. Uses the dual
        bit trick: borrow = ((NOT a AND b) OR (NOT (a XOR b) AND d)) >> 63.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        The formula is the subtractive companion of the additive carry trick.
        For each bit position, a borrow is generated when a=0 and b=1, or
        propagated when a and b agree and the diff bit is 1. Folding gives
        the borrow-out from the top bit position.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Constant time: 5 bitwise ops + 1 shift. No branches.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time by construction.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let not_a be bitwise not a
    Let term1 be not_a bitwise and b
    Let xor_ab be a bitwise xor b
    Let not_xor be bitwise not xor_ab
    Let term2 be not_xor bitwise and diff
    Let combined be term1 bitwise or term2
    Let borrow_bit be combined shifted right by 63
    Let result be borrow_bit bitwise and 1
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Allocation and Construction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_allocate" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Allocate a fresh 64-byte Int512 buffer on the owned heap (Tier 3).
        Buffer is guaranteed zero-initialized by the layout allocator's
        calloc-zero contract, so a fresh allocation represents the value 0.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Delegates to Layout.allocate which guarantees zeroed memory.
        Returns 0 on allocation failure (out of memory).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        O(1) when the pool fast path services the request. Allocation size
        (64 bytes) matches a typical small-bucket size, so allocations are
        cheap and cache-aligned.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Memory is fully zeroed by the allocator; no information leak from
        prior allocations. Caller is responsible for deallocation via
        int512_free to prevent leaks.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let ptr be proc allocate from Layout with INT512_SIZE_BYTES
    Return ptr
End Process

Process called "int512_free" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Release an Int512 buffer back to the owned heap. Caller must ensure
        no aliases remain.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Delegates to Layout.deallocate. Passing 0 is a no-op (idempotent
        free safety).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        O(1) for pool-recycled buffers.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Caller must not use the pointer after this call (use-after-free).
        Memory contents are not zeroed on free; if the buffer held secret
        material, the caller should zero it first via int512_set_zero.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_OK
    End If
    Let dummy be proc deallocate from Layout with a
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_set_zero" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Set all 8 limbs of an Int512 to zero, producing the canonical zero
        value. Required for resetting buffers between operations and for
        zeroing sensitive material before free.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Stores 0 to each limb offset directly via memory_set_int64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 stores, fully unrolled, no branches. Maps to 8 mov instructions
        on x86_64 and equivalent stores on other ISAs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Safe for secret-zeroing as long as the buffer pointer is valid.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let dummy0 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 0, 0
    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 8, 0
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 16, 0
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 24, 0
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 32, 0
    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 40, 0
    Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 48, 0
    Let dummy7 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 56, 0
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_copy" takes src as Integer, dst as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Copy all 8 limbs from src to dst. Required so callers can preserve
        operands when an arithmetic primitive writes to a result buffer that
        might alias an input.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Limb-by-limb load and store via memory_get_int64 / memory_set_int64.
        Safe to call with src == dst (no-op effectively).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 loads + 8 stores, fully unrolled.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        No information leak; constant-time per call.
    @End Security_Scope

    If src is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If dst is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let l0 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 0
    Let l1 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 8
    Let l2 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 16
    Let l3 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 24
    Let l4 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 32
    Let l5 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 40
    Let l6 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 48
    Let l7 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with src, 56
    Let d0 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 0, l0
    Let d1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 8, l1
    Let d2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 16, l2
    Let d3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 24, l3
    Let d4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 32, l4
    Let d5 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 40, l5
    Let d6 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 48, l6
    Let d7 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with dst, 56, l7
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_set_u64" takes a as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Initialize an Int512 from a single 64-bit value: low limb gets value,
        upper 7 limbs zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Stores value at offset 0 and zero at offsets 8..56.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 stores, fully unrolled.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let d0 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 0, value
    Let d1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 8, 0
    Let d2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 16, 0
    Let d3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 24, 0
    Let d4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 32, 0
    Let d5 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 40, 0
    Let d6 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 48, 0
    Let d7 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 56, 0
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Limb Accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_get_limb" takes a as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Read a 64-bit limb at the given index (0..7, 0 = least significant).
        Out-of-range indices return 0 to keep arithmetic loops total over
        index spaces that exceed the limb count.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Index validated; offset computed as index*8 and read via
        memory_get_int64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One load + one branch for bounds check.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Bounds-checked; safe against out-of-range index attacks.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If index is greater than 7:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let offset be index multiplied by 8
    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
    Return value
End Process

Process called "int512_set_limb" takes a as Integer, index as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Write a 64-bit limb at the given index (0..7, 0 = least significant).
        Out-of-range indices are silently dropped to keep iterative
        algorithms safe.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Index validated; offset = index*8; store via memory_set_int64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One store + one branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Bounds-checked.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If index is less than 0:
        Return INT512_OK
    End If
    If index is greater than 7:
        Return INT512_OK
    End If
    Let offset be index multiplied by 8
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset, value
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Predicates
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_is_zero" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Test whether every limb is zero. Returns 1 if so, 0 otherwise.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        OR-folds all 8 limbs; result == 0 iff all limbs were zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 loads + 7 ORs + 1 compare. No branches in the hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time data flow; safe on secret-dependent input.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let l0 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 0
    Let l1 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 8
    Let l2 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 16
    Let l3 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 24
    Let l4 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 32
    Let l5 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 40
    Let l6 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 48
    Let l7 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 56
    Let or01 be l0 bitwise or l1
    Let or23 be l2 bitwise or l3
    Let or45 be l4 bitwise or l5
    Let or67 be l6 bitwise or l7
    Let or0123 be or01 bitwise or or23
    Let or4567 be or45 bitwise or or67
    Let combined be or0123 bitwise or or4567
    If combined is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "int512_compare_unsigned_limb" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compare two 64-bit values as unsigned. Returns -1 if a<b, 0 if equal,
        1 if a>b under unsigned interpretation. Used by the multi-limb
        compare loop. Implemented via the bit trick (a XOR sign_bit) <
        (b XOR sign_bit) which converts unsigned comparison to signed on
        identical two's-complement bit patterns.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Flip the sign bit on both operands; signed comparison then yields
        the unsigned ordering.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Constant time.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time control flow up to the result.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_flip be a bitwise xor INT512_HIGH_BIT_MASK
    Let b_flip be b bitwise xor INT512_HIGH_BIT_MASK
    If a_flip is less than b_flip:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "int512_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Three-way unsigned comparison. Returns -1, 0, or 1. Iterates from
        most significant limb downward so the first differing limb decides
        the ordering.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Loop from limb index 7 down to 0; compare limbs as unsigned 64-bit
        via int512_compare_unsigned_limb. First non-equal limb returns its
        comparison; if all equal, returns 0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Worst case: 8 limb comparisons. Early-exit on first difference.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Data-dependent early exit. For constant-time comparison on secret
        values, the caller should use a dedicated CT routine; this routine
        is optimized for the common consensus-path use case where ordering
        is decided by public values.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 7
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let lb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, offset
        If la is not equal to lb:
            Let result be proc int512_compare_unsigned_limb with la, lb
            Return result
        End If
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Addition and Subtraction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute result = (a + b) mod 2^512 with wrapping semantics. Carry
        is propagated from limb 0 upward; carry out of limb 7 is discarded
        (this is the wrapping behavior).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        For each limb i in 0..7:
          sum_i = a_i + b_i + carry_in
          carry_out = carry from a_i + b_i, plus carry from (a_i+b_i)+carry_in
        Each sub-add's carry is computed via int512_carry_from_add; carries
        are summed because adding three 64-bit values can produce a
        2-bit carry.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 unrolled limbs, each with constant-time carry computation.
        Branch-free in the hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time; suitable for secret values. Wrapping behavior is
        explicit and documented; checked variants raise overflow flags
        instead of silently wrapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let carry be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let lb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, offset
        Let s1 be la plus lb
        Let c1 be proc int512_carry_from_add with la, lb, s1
        Let s2 be s1 plus carry
        Let c2 be proc int512_carry_from_add with s1, carry, s2
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, s2
        Set carry to c1 plus c2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_add_checked" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer, overflow_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Same as int512_add but writes the carry-out of the top limb to
        overflow_out. Caller observes whether a + b exceeded 2^512 - 1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Mirrors int512_add but preserves the final carry value and writes
        it to *overflow_out via memory_set_int64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One additional store relative to int512_add.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If overflow_out is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let carry be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let lb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, offset
        Let s1 be la plus lb
        Let c1 be proc int512_carry_from_add with la, lb, s1
        Let s2 be s1 plus carry
        Let c2 be proc int512_carry_from_add with s1, carry, s2
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, s2
        Set carry to c1 plus c2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let dummy_ov be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with overflow_out, 0, carry
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute result = (a - b) mod 2^512 with wrapping semantics. Borrow
        is propagated from limb 0 upward.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        For each limb i:
          tmp1 = a_i - b_i
          b1 = borrow from a_i - b_i
          tmp2 = tmp1 - borrow_in
          b2 = borrow from tmp1 - borrow_in
        Borrows are summed because subtracting three 64-bit values yields
        at most a 2-bit borrow.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 unrolled limbs, constant-time borrow computation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let borrow be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let lb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, offset
        Let d1 be la minus lb
        Let b1 be proc int512_borrow_from_sub with la, lb, d1
        Let d2 be d1 minus borrow
        Let b2 be proc int512_borrow_from_sub with d1, borrow, d2
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, d2
        Set borrow to b1 plus b2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Bitwise Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_bit_and" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Element-wise bitwise AND across all 8 limbs.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Loop 0..7: result_i = a_i AND b_i.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 loads from each of a and b, 8 ANDs, 8 stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let lb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, offset
        Let r be la bitwise and lb
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, r
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_bit_or" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Element-wise bitwise OR across all 8 limbs.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Loop 0..7: result_i = a_i OR b_i.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Same pattern as int512_bit_and.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let lb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, offset
        Let r be la bitwise or lb
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, r
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_bit_xor" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Element-wise bitwise XOR across all 8 limbs.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Loop 0..7: result_i = a_i XOR b_i.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Same pattern as int512_bit_and.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let lb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, offset
        Let r be la bitwise xor lb
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, r
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_bit_not" takes a as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        One's complement: flip every bit. Equivalent to (2^512 - 1) - a.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Loop 0..7: result_i = NOT a_i.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        8 loads, 8 NOTs, 8 stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let la be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, offset
        Let r be bitwise not la
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, r
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Shifts
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_shift_left" takes a as Integer, bits as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Logical left shift by `bits` positions (0..511). Vacated low bits
        become zero; bits shifted past position 511 are lost (this is the
        wrapping semantics for mod 2^512).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Decompose into limb-shift and intra-limb-shift.
        limb_shift = bits / 64; bit_shift = bits mod 64.
        For each output limb i (top-down to allow aliasing source==result):
          let src_hi_index = i - limb_shift
          let src_lo_index = src_hi_index - 1
          if bit_shift == 0:
              result_i = src[src_hi_index] (or 0 if out of range)
          else:
              hi = (src[src_hi_index] << bit_shift)
              lo = (src[src_lo_index] >> (64 - bit_shift))
              result_i = hi | lo (with out-of-range source treated as 0)
        Iterating top-down (from limb 7 down to 0) means each result limb
        is written after its source has been fully read, so source==result
        is safe.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Constant-time for fixed `bits`. Per-limb cost: 2 loads, 1 OR,
        1 store, plus shift operations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Bounds-validated: bits < 0 or bits >= 512 returns error.
        Constant-time data flow.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If bits is less than 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_INVALID_SHIFT
    End If
    If bits is greater than or equal to INT512_BIT_WIDTH:
        Note: Shifting by >= width yields zero
        Let zero_ret be proc int512_set_zero with result
        Return INT512_OK
    End If

    Let limb_shift be bits divided by 64
    Let bit_shift be bits modulo by 64

    Note: Load all 8 source limbs into local registers to guarantee
    Note: aliasing safety (read all before writing any).
    Let s0 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 0
    Let s1 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 8
    Let s2 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 16
    Let s3 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 24
    Let s4 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 32
    Let s5 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 40
    Let s6 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 48
    Let s7 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 56

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let hi_index be i minus limb_shift
        Let lo_index be hi_index minus 1
        Let hi_limb be 0
        Let lo_limb be 0
        If hi_index is greater than or equal to 0:
            If hi_index is equal to 0:
                Set hi_limb to s0
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 1:
                Set hi_limb to s1
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 2:
                Set hi_limb to s2
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 3:
                Set hi_limb to s3
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 4:
                Set hi_limb to s4
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 5:
                Set hi_limb to s5
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 6:
                Set hi_limb to s6
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 7:
                Set hi_limb to s7
            End If
        End If
        If lo_index is greater than or equal to 0:
            If lo_index is equal to 0:
                Set lo_limb to s0
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 1:
                Set lo_limb to s1
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 2:
                Set lo_limb to s2
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 3:
                Set lo_limb to s3
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 4:
                Set lo_limb to s4
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 5:
                Set lo_limb to s5
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 6:
                Set lo_limb to s6
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 7:
                Set lo_limb to s7
            End If
        End If
        Let out_value be 0
        If bit_shift is equal to 0:
            Set out_value to hi_limb
        Otherwise:
            Let hi_part be hi_limb shifted left by bit_shift
            Let inv_shift be 64 minus bit_shift
            Let lo_part be lo_limb shifted right by inv_shift
            Note: Mask off any sign-extension that arithmetic right shift
            Note: may have introduced on the lo_part. The high bits above
            Note: bit_shift in lo_part must be zero.
            Let lo_mask_width be bit_shift
            Let lo_mask be 0
            If lo_mask_width is equal to 64:
                Set lo_mask to bitwise not 0
            Otherwise:
                Let mask_base be 1 shifted left by lo_mask_width
                Set lo_mask to mask_base minus 1
            End If
            Let lo_masked be lo_part bitwise and lo_mask
            Set out_value to hi_part bitwise or lo_masked
        End If
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, out_value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_shift_right" takes a as Integer, bits as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Logical right shift by `bits` positions (0..511). Vacated high bits
        become zero; bits shifted past position 0 are lost.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Symmetric to int512_shift_left: each result limb is composed from
        a "low" source limb (right-shifted by bit_shift) and a "high"
        source limb (left-shifted by 64-bit_shift). Loads all source limbs
        first to allow aliasing source==result.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Constant-time for fixed `bits`.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Bounds-validated; constant-time data flow.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If bits is less than 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_INVALID_SHIFT
    End If
    If bits is greater than or equal to INT512_BIT_WIDTH:
        Let zero_ret be proc int512_set_zero with result
        Return INT512_OK
    End If

    Let limb_shift be bits divided by 64
    Let bit_shift be bits modulo by 64

    Let s0 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 0
    Let s1 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 8
    Let s2 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 16
    Let s3 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 24
    Let s4 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 32
    Let s5 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 40
    Let s6 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 48
    Let s7 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 56

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let lo_index be i plus limb_shift
        Let hi_index be lo_index plus 1
        Let lo_limb be 0
        Let hi_limb be 0
        If lo_index is less than or equal to 7:
            If lo_index is equal to 0:
                Set lo_limb to s0
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 1:
                Set lo_limb to s1
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 2:
                Set lo_limb to s2
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 3:
                Set lo_limb to s3
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 4:
                Set lo_limb to s4
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 5:
                Set lo_limb to s5
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 6:
                Set lo_limb to s6
            End If
            If lo_index is equal to 7:
                Set lo_limb to s7
            End If
        End If
        If hi_index is less than or equal to 7:
            If hi_index is equal to 0:
                Set hi_limb to s0
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 1:
                Set hi_limb to s1
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 2:
                Set hi_limb to s2
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 3:
                Set hi_limb to s3
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 4:
                Set hi_limb to s4
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 5:
                Set hi_limb to s5
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 6:
                Set hi_limb to s6
            End If
            If hi_index is equal to 7:
                Set hi_limb to s7
            End If
        End If
        Let out_value be 0
        If bit_shift is equal to 0:
            Set out_value to lo_limb
        Otherwise:
            Let lo_part be lo_limb shifted right by bit_shift
            Note: Mask the lo_part so any arithmetic-right-shift sign
            Note: extension is cleared (logical shift semantics).
            Let lo_keep_width be 64 minus bit_shift
            Let lo_mask be 0
            If lo_keep_width is equal to 64:
                Set lo_mask to bitwise not 0
            Otherwise:
                Let mask_base be 1 shifted left by lo_keep_width
                Set lo_mask to mask_base minus 1
            End If
            Let lo_masked be lo_part bitwise and lo_mask
            Let inv_shift be 64 minus bit_shift
            Let hi_part be hi_limb shifted left by inv_shift
            Set out_value to lo_masked bitwise or hi_part
        End If
        Let offset be i multiplied by 8
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, offset, out_value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: 32-bit Half-Limb Multiplication (Schoolbook Building Block)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_mul_64x64_to_128_lo" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute the low 64 bits of (a * b) where a, b are unsigned 64-bit
        values. Native multiplication wraps to 64 bits, so this is just
        the wrapping product.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Return a * b (the bootstrap compiler emits an imulq which produces
        the low 64 bits of the 128-bit product, identical to mulq's low
        result for unsigned multiplication).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Single multiplication instruction.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time (single mul).
    @End Security_Scope
    Return a multiplied by b
End Process

Process called "int512_mul_64x64_to_128_hi" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute the high 64 bits of the 128-bit unsigned product a * b.
        Since the bootstrap compiler does not expose a 128-bit type or
        the mulhi instruction, we decompose into 32-bit halves:
          a = a_hi * 2^32 + a_lo
          b = b_hi * 2^32 + b_lo
          a*b = a_hi*b_hi*2^64 + (a_hi*b_lo + a_lo*b_hi)*2^32 + a_lo*b_lo
        The high 64 bits are extracted by summing the high-32-bit-carries
        from the cross terms plus a_hi*b_hi.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Split a and b into 32-bit halves; compute the four 64-bit partial
        products (each fits because 32*32 = 64 bits max); sum the products
        column-by-column, capturing the carry into the high 64 bits.

        Layout (each cell is 32 bits):
                                a_hi   a_lo
                              x b_hi   b_lo
                              -----------
                             lo_lo (low 64 bits = [hi32(lo_lo) | lo32(lo_lo)])
                       hi_lo + lo_hi  (each is a 64-bit product placed at offset 32)
              hi_hi (placed at offset 64)
        We sum column 32 (the middle column) including hi32(lo_lo); the
        carry out of bit 95 (column 64+) goes into the high result.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        4 multiplications, several shifts/adds. The bootstrap compiler
        cannot expose mulq's RDX:RAX output as a single instruction, so
        this is the portable fallback. Maps to the same operations a C
        compiler would emit on a target without __int128.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time: no branches on operand bits.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask32 be INT512_LIMB_MASK_LOW32
    Let a_lo be a bitwise and mask32
    Let a_hi_signed be a shifted right by 32
    Let a_hi be a_hi_signed bitwise and mask32
    Let b_lo be b bitwise and mask32
    Let b_hi_signed be b shifted right by 32
    Let b_hi be b_hi_signed bitwise and mask32

    Note: Four 32x32 -> 64 partial products (always fit in 64 bits unsigned)
    Let lo_lo be a_lo multiplied by b_lo
    Let hi_lo be a_hi multiplied by b_lo
    Let lo_hi be a_lo multiplied by b_hi
    Let hi_hi be a_hi multiplied by b_hi

    Note: Extract the high 32 bits of lo_lo (the carry from column 0 to
    Note: column 32). Note: arithmetic right shift may sign-extend; mask.
    Let lo_lo_high_signed be lo_lo shifted right by 32
    Let lo_lo_high be lo_lo_high_signed bitwise and mask32

    Note: Sum the middle column at offset 32: hi_lo + lo_hi + lo_lo_high.
    Note: Each summand is <= (2^32 - 1)^2 ~= 2^64 - 2^33 + 1, plus
    Note: 2^32 - 1; total < 2 * 2^64 so we capture carry across two adds.
    Let mid_a be hi_lo plus lo_lo_high
    Let carry_a be proc int512_carry_from_add with hi_lo, lo_lo_high, mid_a
    Let mid be mid_a plus lo_hi
    Let carry_b be proc int512_carry_from_add with mid_a, lo_hi, mid

    Note: The high 64 bits of the full 128-bit product are:
    Note:   hi_hi + (carry from middle column) * 2^64-contribution
    Note:   + (mid's upper 32 bits as the carry into column 64)
    Let mid_high_signed be mid shifted right by 32
    Let mid_high be mid_high_signed bitwise and mask32

    Note: Combine: hi_hi sits naturally at offset 64. Add mid_high and
    Note: the cross-column carry shifted up by 32 bits.
    Let total_carry be carry_a plus carry_b
    Let carry_contribution be total_carry shifted left by 32
    Let hi_result_partial be hi_hi plus mid_high
    Let hi_result be hi_result_partial plus carry_contribution
    Return hi_result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Multiplication
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_mul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute result = (a * b) mod 2^512 with wrapping semantics. Uses
        schoolbook multiplication: for each (i, j) limb pair where i+j < 8,
        accumulate a_i * b_j into the result at limb i+j (and carry into
        i+j+1).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Initialize result to zero. For each i in 0..7, for each j in 0..7
        with i+j < 8, compute the 128-bit product a_i * b_j (lo and hi
        halves via int512_mul_64x64_to_128_lo / _hi), then add lo to
        result[i+j] and hi to result[i+j+1], propagating carry.

        Aliasing safety: if `result` overlaps `a` or `b`, we copy operands
        to local 8-limb arrays in `a_local` / `b_local` first. To avoid
        allocating temporary buffers, we instead snapshot all 8 limbs of
        each operand into local variables before zeroing `result`.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Schoolbook is O(n^2) on limbs: 36 full and partial multiplications
        for 8x8 limbs with truncation at limb 7. No Karatsuba threshold
        crossed at this width (Karatsuba breaks even around 16+ limbs on
        modern CPUs).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Wrapping semantics documented. Constant-time data flow (no
        operand-dependent branches in the inner loop).
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Note: Snapshot a and b into locals (8 64-bit values each) so the result
    Note: buffer can safely alias a or b.
    Let a0 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 0
    Let a1 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 8
    Let a2 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 16
    Let a3 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 24
    Let a4 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 32
    Let a5 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 40
    Let a6 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 48
    Let a7 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, 56
    Let b0 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 0
    Let b1 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 8
    Let b2 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 16
    Let b3 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 24
    Let b4 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 32
    Let b5 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 40
    Let b6 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 48
    Let b7 be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, 56

    Let zero_ret be proc int512_set_zero with result

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 8:
        Let j be 0
        Let ai be 0
        If i is equal to 0:
            Set ai to a0
        End If
        If i is equal to 1:
            Set ai to a1
        End If
        If i is equal to 2:
            Set ai to a2
        End If
        If i is equal to 3:
            Set ai to a3
        End If
        If i is equal to 4:
            Set ai to a4
        End If
        If i is equal to 5:
            Set ai to a5
        End If
        If i is equal to 6:
            Set ai to a6
        End If
        If i is equal to 7:
            Set ai to a7
        End If

        While j is less than 8:
            Let dest be i plus j
            If dest is less than 8:
                Let bj be 0
                If j is equal to 0:
                    Set bj to b0
                End If
                If j is equal to 1:
                    Set bj to b1
                End If
                If j is equal to 2:
                    Set bj to b2
                End If
                If j is equal to 3:
                    Set bj to b3
                End If
                If j is equal to 4:
                    Set bj to b4
                End If
                If j is equal to 5:
                    Set bj to b5
                End If
                If j is equal to 6:
                    Set bj to b6
                End If
                If j is equal to 7:
                    Set bj to b7
                End If

                Let p_lo be proc int512_mul_64x64_to_128_lo with ai, bj
                Let p_hi be proc int512_mul_64x64_to_128_hi with ai, bj

                Note: Add p_lo to result[dest] with carry propagation upward.
                Let dest_offset be dest multiplied by 8
                Let cur_dest be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with result, dest_offset
                Let new_dest be cur_dest plus p_lo
                Let carry_dest be proc int512_carry_from_add with cur_dest, p_lo, new_dest
                Let dummy_a be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, dest_offset, new_dest

                Note: Add p_hi + carry_dest to result[dest+1], propagating
                Note: any further carry through all higher limbs.
                Let next_dest be dest plus 1
                If next_dest is less than 8:
                    Let next_offset be next_dest multiplied by 8
                    Let cur_next be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with result, next_offset
                    Let added_hi be cur_next plus p_hi
                    Let carry_hi be proc int512_carry_from_add with cur_next, p_hi, added_hi
                    Let final_next be added_hi plus carry_dest
                    Let carry_cd be proc int512_carry_from_add with added_hi, carry_dest, final_next
                    Let dummy_b be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, next_offset, final_next
                    Let propagate_carry be carry_hi plus carry_cd
                    Let k be next_dest plus 1
                    While k is less than 8:
                        If propagate_carry is equal to 0:
                            Set k to 8
                        Otherwise:
                            Let k_offset be k multiplied by 8
                            Let cur_k be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with result, k_offset
                            Let new_k be cur_k plus propagate_carry
                            Let carry_k be proc int512_carry_from_add with cur_k, propagate_carry, new_k
                            Let dummy_k be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with result, k_offset, new_k
                            Set propagate_carry to carry_k
                            Set k to k plus 1
                        End If
                    End While
                End If
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Division and Modulo (Long Division)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "int512_divmod" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, quotient_out as Integer, remainder_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Unsigned long division: compute q, r such that a = q * b + r,
        0 <= r < b. Uses binary long division (shift-and-subtract), which
        is portable and deterministic across all platforms.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Algorithm (classical schoolbook binary long division):
          if b == 0: return INT512_ERR_DIVIDE_BY_ZERO
          quotient = 0, remainder = 0
          for bit_index from 511 downto 0:
              remainder = (remainder << 1) | bit(a, bit_index)
              if remainder >= b:
                  remainder -= b
                  set bit_index of quotient
          write quotient, remainder

        We use temporary scratch buffers for the in-progress remainder.
        Aliasing safety: snapshot a and b into local arrays via copy() to
        scratch buffers, then write quotient_out / remainder_out at the
        end.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        512 iterations, each doing one shift-left, one limb compare, one
        conditional subtract, one bit-set. Total cost dominated by the
        512 shift-left passes (each O(limbs)).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Division by zero is explicitly rejected with INT512_ERR_DIVIDE_BY_ZERO;
        callers must check the return value. Data flow is value-dependent
        (the inner comparison branches on remainder >= divisor); this is
        acceptable for non-secret divisors.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If quotient_out is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If remainder_out is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let is_div_zero be proc int512_is_zero with b
    If is_div_zero is equal to 1:
        Return INT512_ERR_DIVIDE_BY_ZERO
    End If

    Note: Allocate scratch buffers. We need 4: a_copy (to safely read the
    Note: dividend bits even if a aliases quotient_out / remainder_out),
    Note: b_copy (similarly safe), remainder_work, and quotient_work.
    Let a_copy be proc int512_allocate
    If a_copy is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let b_copy be proc int512_allocate
    If b_copy is equal to 0:
        Let dummy_free_a be proc int512_free with a_copy
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let remainder_work be proc int512_allocate
    If remainder_work is equal to 0:
        Let dummy_free_a2 be proc int512_free with a_copy
        Let dummy_free_b2 be proc int512_free with b_copy
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let quotient_work be proc int512_allocate
    If quotient_work is equal to 0:
        Let dummy_free_a3 be proc int512_free with a_copy
        Let dummy_free_b3 be proc int512_free with b_copy
        Let dummy_free_r3 be proc int512_free with remainder_work
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let cp_a be proc int512_copy with a, a_copy
    Let cp_b be proc int512_copy with b, b_copy
    Let z_r be proc int512_set_zero with remainder_work
    Let z_q be proc int512_set_zero with quotient_work

    Let bit_index be 511
    While bit_index is greater than or equal to 0:
        Note: Shift remainder_work left by 1.
        Let dummy_shl be proc int512_shift_left with remainder_work, 1, remainder_work

        Note: Extract bit `bit_index` from a_copy and OR into remainder_work bit 0.
        Let limb_idx be bit_index divided by 64
        Let bit_in_limb be bit_index modulo by 64
        Let offset be limb_idx multiplied by 8
        Let a_limb be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a_copy, offset
        Let shifted_limb be a_limb shifted right by bit_in_limb
        Let dividend_bit be shifted_limb bitwise and 1

        Let cur_remainder_low be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with remainder_work, 0
        Let new_remainder_low be cur_remainder_low bitwise or dividend_bit
        Let set_low be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with remainder_work, 0, new_remainder_low

        Note: Compare remainder_work to b_copy. If >=, subtract and set quotient bit.
        Let cmp be proc int512_compare with remainder_work, b_copy
        If cmp is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let dummy_sub be proc int512_sub with remainder_work, b_copy, remainder_work
            Let q_limb_idx be bit_index divided by 64
            Let q_bit_in_limb be bit_index modulo by 64
            Let q_offset be q_limb_idx multiplied by 8
            Let q_cur be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with quotient_work, q_offset
            Let q_bit_mask be 1 shifted left by q_bit_in_limb
            Let q_new be q_cur bitwise or q_bit_mask
            Let dummy_qset be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with quotient_work, q_offset, q_new
        End If

        Set bit_index to bit_index minus 1
    End While

    Note: Copy results out.
    Let cp_q be proc int512_copy with quotient_work, quotient_out
    Let cp_r be proc int512_copy with remainder_work, remainder_out

    Let dummy_free_a4 be proc int512_free with a_copy
    Let dummy_free_b4 be proc int512_free with b_copy
    Let dummy_free_r4 be proc int512_free with remainder_work
    Let dummy_free_q4 be proc int512_free with quotient_work
    Return INT512_OK
End Process

Process called "int512_div" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, quotient_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute quotient = a / b (unsigned). Convenience wrapper around
        int512_divmod that discards the remainder.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Allocates a scratch remainder buffer, calls divmod, then frees the
        scratch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Same cost as divmod plus one allocation/deallocation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Same as divmod.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If quotient_out is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let r_scratch be proc int512_allocate
    If r_scratch is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let rc be proc int512_divmod with a, b, quotient_out, r_scratch
    Let dummy_free be proc int512_free with r_scratch
    Return rc
End Process

Process called "int512_mod" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, remainder_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Compute remainder = a mod b (unsigned). Convenience wrapper around
        int512_divmod that discards the quotient.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Allocates a scratch quotient buffer, calls divmod, then frees it.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Same cost as divmod plus one allocation/deallocation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Same as divmod.
    @End Security_Scope

    If a is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    If remainder_out is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let q_scratch be proc int512_allocate
    If q_scratch is equal to 0:
        Return INT512_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Let rc be proc int512_divmod with a, b, q_scratch, remainder_out
    Let dummy_free be proc int512_free with q_scratch
    Return rc
End Process
